Nanolasers couplés en régime quantique

Coupled nanolasers in the quantum regime

   Mots clés
   Nanolasers, cristaux photoniques, optique quantique
   Profil et compétences recherchées
   Connaissance dans au moins deux des domaines suivants:
   - photonique, optique non-linéaire
   - physique quantique
   - nanotechnologie
   Français ou anglais parlé.
   Niveau d'anglais requis: Intermédiaire supérieur: Vous pouvez utiliser
   la langue de manière efficace et vous exprimer précisément.
   Présentation détaillée du projet doctoral
   In our group at C2N, we have recently demonstrated spontaneous symmetry
   breaking (SSB) in a nanophotonic molecule [Nature Photonics 2015].
   Namely, we have shown a pitchfork bifurcation of the intensity of the
   lasing mode of two coupled photonic crystal nanocavities. Such a double
   potential well-system exhibits a transition from a delocalized state to
   two coexisting states mirror images of each other where photons are
   localized in each cavity. This was made possible thanks to the
   particular engineering of the coupling barrier, allowing fine control
   of both the amplitude and the sign of the evanescent coupling. We
   furthe explore the photon emission statistics and demonstrated
   superbunching effects [Physical Review X 2018]. These demonstration
   were performed with a relatively small number of photons (100).
   The PhD project plans to lower down the number of photons to enter the
   quantum regime. This will be achieved by increasing the nanocavities
   spontaneous emission rate into the laser modes. We plan to investigated
   different coupled nanolasers topologies and explore facinating
   nonlinear dynamical regimes in the low photon number - quantum- regime.
   esign and fabrication of photonic crystal nanolasers to nonlinear
   dynamics and quantum optics theoretical and experimental recognized
   achievements.
   Thématiques Contexte
   In this PhD we are at the crossing of nanophotonics, semiconductor
   physics, quantum optics.
   Objectif et contexte
   Demonstration of efficient room temperature quantum coupled nanolasers
   C2N recently move to the Paris-Saclay campus and constitute an unique
   place to efficiently combine nanotechnology and nonlinear dynamics
   experiments with quantum information as an ultimate goal.
   Méthode
   The PhD will adquire several skills that will open many academic and
   industrial possibilities for his/her future carreer. This will be
   achieved with the help of experts on photonic design, nanofabrication
   in the C2N clean room, photon counting measurements, time resolved
   nonlinear ynamics measurements.
   Résultats attendus
   We expect to develop room-temperature efficient coupled (2, 3, ...N,
   quantum nanolasers in different geometrical topologies.
   Précision sur l'encadrement
   Le doctorant sera co-encadré au quotidien et participera aux activitiés
   et réunions du groupe TONIQ.
   Conditions scientifiques matérielles (conditions de sécurité
   spécifiques)
   et financières du projet de recherches
   Le laboratoire a récément démenagé et le candidat bénéficiera d'un
   environnement complet expérimental et technologique. La thèse
   bénéficiera des collaborations se déroulant dans le cadre de l'ANR
   UNIQ.
   Objectifs de valorisation des travaux de recherche du doctorant :
   diffusion,
   publication et confidentialité, droit à la propriété intellectuelle,...
   We expect publications in the best international reviews of the field
   and in general scientific reviews.
   Collaborations envisag&eacutees
   Some collaborations are ongoing under the ANR UNIQ project.
   Références bibliographiques
   Our recent publications on the subject.
   1. Spontaneous mirror-symmetry breaking in coupled photonic crystal
   nanolasers, P. Hamel et al., Nat. Phot. 9, 311 (2015)
   2. Asymmetric mode scattering in strongly coupled photonic crystal
   nanolasers, M Marconi et al., Optics Letters 41 (24), 5628 (2016)
   3. Far-from-Equilibrium Route to Superthermal Light in Bimodal
   Nanolasers , M. Marconi et al. Phys. Rev. X 8, 011013 (2018)
   Complément sur le sujet
   https://toniq.c2n.universite-paris-saclay.fr/en/activities/fewphotons/
   Keywords
   Nanolasers, photonic crystals, quantum optics
   Profile and skills required
   Skills on at least two of the following fields:
   - photonics, nonlinear optics.
   - quantum physics.
   - nanotechnology
   Fluent English or French
   Niveau d'anglais requis: Intermédiaire supérieur: Vous pouvez utiliser
   la langue de manière efficace et vous exprimer précisément.
   Project description
   In our group at C2N, we have recently demonstrated spontaneous symmetry
   breaking (SSB) in a nanophotonic molecule [Nature Photonics 2015].
   Namely, we have shown a pitchfork bifurcation of the intensity of the
   lasing mode of two coupled photonic crystal nanocavities. Such a double
   potential well-system exhibits a transition from a delocalized state to
   two coexisting states mirror images of each other where photons are
   localized in each cavity. This was made possible thanks to the
   particular engineering of the coupling barrier, allowing fine control
   of both the amplitude and the sign of the evanescent coupling. We
   furthe explore the photon emission statistics and demonstrated
   superbunching effects [Physical Review X 2018]. These demonstration
   were performed with a relatively small number of photons (100).
   The PhD project plans to lower down the number of photons to enter the
   quantum regime. This will be achieved by increasing the nanocavities
   spontaneous emission rate into the laser modes. We plan to investigated
   different coupled nanolasers topologies and explore facinating
   nonlinear dynamical regimes in the low photon number - quantum- regime.
   This is an emerging feald were our team has interdisciplinary skills,
   from design and fabrication of photonic crystal nanolasers to nonlinear
   dynamics and quantum optics theoretical and experimental recognized
   achievements.
   References
